International Tributes to the History of Flight
First Airmail Across the Pacific
The historic journey of the "China Clipper" began as
the amplified voice of Pan American Airways Presi-
dent, Juan T. Trippe, reverberated above the Alameda
airbase,
...the transpacific airway is ready to inau-
gurate airmail service of the United States Post Office
from the mainland, across the Pacific to the
Philippines..."
On November 22, 1935, the Martin M-130 flying
boat, known as the "China Clipper," began its jour-
ney. For the first time in history, the people on the
east and west sides of the Pacific would be linked.
This flight was a significant advance for Pan Am in its
effort to build a commercial airline network.
The full-color cachet shows the "China Clipper"
high above the San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge on
its return flight.
Mint stamp: The mint stamp on this Cover was issued
by Zaire in 1978. The aircraft in the foreground is the
Sikorsky S-42 which was the first long range "Clip-
per" ship. It was used by Pan Am to survey the route
ultimately used by the "China Clipper."
Postmark: This Cover was postmarked in Alameda,
California, the origination site of the "China Clipper"
flight, on November 22,1983, the anniversary of the
first airmail flight across the Pacific.
